  "page_content": {
    "introduction": [
      "This calculator helps boat buyers and owners estimate how extra payments (recurring, one-time, or annual lumps) change the amortization of a boat loan. Use it to compare scheduled payments, payoff time, total interest, and interest saved compared to the baseline schedule.",
      "The tool offers multiple scenario methods so you can see immediate and longer-term effects of consistent extra contributions or occasional lump-sum payments. Values are estimates intended for planning and comparison."
    ],
    "methodology": [
      "Calculations follow standard amortization mathematics: periodic interest rate = annual rate / payments per year. The scheduled payment solves the annuity equation for fixed-rate loans.",
      "Recurring extra payments are modeled by increasing the per-period payment and solving the closed-form formula for the number of periods required to amortize the principal. One-time extra payments are applied to the outstanding balance at the chosen period and the remaining term is re-estimated. Annual lumps are approximated by distributing the annual lump across the year's periods to create an effective per-period extra; for precise annual-lump amortization use an iterative amortization schedule.",
      "Results are estimates and assume constant interest rate, timely application of extras, and no fees or prepayment penalties. If your loan contract includes prepayment penalties, fees, or variable rates, use the amortization schedule in your loan documents or contact your lender."
    ],
    "how_is_calculated": [
      "Periodic interest rate r = annual_interest_rate / 100 / payments_per_year.",
      "Scheduled payment (annuity formula): payment = P * r / (1 - (1 + r)^-N) where N = term_years * payments_per_year.",
      "For recurring extra, payoff periods n satisfies: n = -ln(1 - r * P / payment_with_extra) / ln(1 + r).",
      "For a one-time extra at period k, remaining balance before the lump is computed from the standard outstanding balance formula; the lump reduces principal and remaining periods are re-solved using the annuity inverse.",
      "Annual lump-sum effect is approximated by distributing the annual lump as an equal per-period amount: effective_extra_per_period = annual_extra_amount / payments_per_year; then recurring formula is used."
    ],
    "examples": [
      "Example 1: $30,000 principal at 6.5% annual, 10 years, monthly payments. Adding $50 to each monthly payment reduces payoff time and total interest; the calculator reports estimated years saved and interest saved.",
      "Example 2: Same loan with a $3,000 one-time extra applied after 12 payments. The tool estimates remaining balance before the lump, new principal after the lump, and the new estimated payoff time and total interest."
    ],
    "faqs": [
      {
        "question": "Are these results exact for my loan?",
        "answer": "Results are estimates based on standard fixed-rate amortization formulas and the inputs you provide. Exact amounts may differ if your lender compounds interest differently, charges fees, applies payments on a particular schedule, or enforces prepayment rules. Use these estimates for planning and consult your loan statement or lender for precise figures."
      },
      {
        "question": "What if my loan imposes prepayment penalties or fees?",
        "answer": "This calculator does not model prepayment penalties, fees, or escrow changes. If your loan agreement includes such conditions, review those contract terms or contact your lender before making extra payments."
      },
      {
        "question": "What inputs can cause errors or non‑real results?",
        "answer": "If the extra payment (or effective payment) is less than the interest charged each period (periodic_rate * principal), the closed-form inverse for payoff periods is not valid and results may be undefined. Also, very large one-time extras can lead to negative remaining principal in the simplified formulas; treat such outputs as 'paid in full at or before that period' and confirm with an amortization schedule."
      },
      {
        "question": "How accurate is the annual-lump approximation?",
        "answer": "The annual-lump method approximates the effect by distributing the lump across periods in the year. It gives a practical estimate but is not exact. For exact treatment, apply a one-time-lump calculation for each annual lump iteratively or generate a full amortization schedule that records each lump application."
      }
    ],
    "glossary": [
      {
        "term": "Principal",
        "definition": "The original loan amount on which interest is calculated."
      },
      {
        "term": "Scheduled payment",
        "definition": "The regular periodic payment required by the loan terms to amortize the loan over the original term, excluding extras."
      },
      {
        "term": "Extra payment",
        "definition": "Additional payment above the scheduled payment applied to principal to reduce interest and shorten payoff time."
      },
      {
        "term": "Payoff periods",
        "definition": "Number of payment periods remaining until the loan is fully repaid under the scenario being modeled."
      },
      {
        "term": "Periodic interest rate",
        "definition": "The interest rate applied each payment period, equal to the annual rate divided by payments per year."
      }
    ],
    "summary": [
      "This tool compares baseline amortization with recurring, one-time, and annual-lump extra-payment strategies. Use it to estimate time and interest savings.",
      "It provides practical approximations and flags common limits where closed-form formulas are not valid. For legally binding payoff amounts, rely on your lender's payoff statement or an exact amortization schedule."
    ],
